<paper id="1571051149"><title>Petri nets and algebraic calculi of processes</title><year>1985</year><authors><author org="Inria - Sophia Antipolis" id="1982484711">Gérard Boudol</author><author org="BULL, Centre de recherches" id="2579278490">Gérard Roucairol</author><author org="Inria - Sophia Antipolis" id="2197689560">Robert de Simone</author></authors><n_citation>16</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>103034903</reference><reference>1526191973</reference><reference>1882941837</reference><reference>1908424597</reference><reference>1978972515</reference><reference>1979462141</reference><reference>1988879351</reference><reference>2001748564</reference><reference>2024074683</reference><reference>2062836726</reference><reference>2070157304</reference><reference>2137865376</reference><reference>2167954650</reference></references><venue id="1204434967" type="C">Applications and Theory of Petri Nets</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0016205</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.43104">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.67383">Petri net</keyword><keyword weight="0.46791">Algebraic number</keyword><keyword weight="0.41927">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.68183">Stochastic Petri net</keyword><keyword weight="0.62809">Process architecture</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We show that, as transition systems, Petri nets may be expressed by terms of a calculus of processes which is a variant of Milneru0027s SCCS. We then prove that the class of labelled nets forms a subcalculus, thus an algebra, with juxtaposition, adding condition and labelling as primitive operations. Finally we introduce rational machines which express explicit synchronizations on nets.</abstract></paper>